nstein condensate. In doing so, it traces the history of radiation and heat capacity theory from the mid-19th century to the present. It describes early attempts to understand heat and light radiation and proceeds through the theory of the heat capacity of solids. It arrives at the theory of superconductivity and superfluidity--the astonishing property of some liquids to crawl spontaneously up and out of their containers, and the ability of some gases to cause light to pause and take a moment's rest from its inexorable flight forward in time. Couched in the terminology of traditional physical chemistry, this book is accessible to chemists, engineers, materials scientists, mathematicians, mathematical biologists, indeed to anyone with a command of first-year calculus. In course work, it is a collateral text to third semester or advanced physical chemistry, introductory statistical mechanics, statistical thermodynamics, or introductory quantum chemistry. The book connects with mainstream physical chemistry by treating boson and fermion influences in molecular spectroscopy, statistical thermodynamics, molecular energetics, entropy, heat capacities (especially of metals), superconductivity, and superfluidity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBlackbody radiation. 0aBose-Einstein condensation. 0aSpecific heat. 7aSCIENCE / Chemistry / Physical & Theoretical.2bisacsh  aDebye equation.  aDebye temperature.  aEinstein coefficients.  aFermi-Dirac counting.  aLagrange's method.  aPlanck equation.  aabsorptivity.  aarrangement.  ablackbody.  abosons.  achemical potential.  aconfiguration.  adegrees of freedom.  aelectron gas.  aenergy density.  aentropy.  afermions.  aharmonic oscillator.  aheat capacity.  aintensity.  amagnetic trapping.  amolar heat capacity.  anumber density.  